My favorite fruit is mango.

01:11.113 --> 01:16.285
My favorite vegetables
are spinach and Bibb lettuce.

01:16.368 --> 01:18.245
Is apples and...

01:20.247 --> 01:21.164
Is apples.

01:21.248 --> 01:22.667
Carrots.

01:22.750 --> 01:25.127
Uh, spinach.

01:26.045 --> 01:28.380
My name is Joe Cross.

01:28.463 --> 01:30.215
<i>And I'm sitting here with a bunch of kids,</i>

01:30.299 --> 01:32.175
<i>and we're talking food.</i>

01:33.761 --> 01:34.679
<i>About 10 years ago,</i>

01:34.762 --> 01:38.140
<i>I was struggling with obesity</i>
<i>and chronic disease.</i>

01:38.223 --> 01:40.643
<i>So, I made some pretty big changes,</i>

01:40.727 --> 01:41.936
<i>became a healthy eater,</i>

01:42.020 --> 01:45.230
<i>and made a documentary about the process.</i>

01:45.314 --> 01:49.027
<i>Little did I know that my film </i>
<i>would resonate with so many people.</i>

01:49.109 --> 01:52.321
<i>And the success of that film</i>
<i>has sent me all over the world,</i>

01:52.404 --> 01:55.867
<i>talking to tens of thousands of people</i>
<i>about their health</i>

01:55.950 --> 01:58.118
<i>and the topics that matter to them.</i>

01:58.201 --> 02:00.830
And I tell you, the number one question
that keeps coming up

02:00.913 --> 02:02.999
<i>is "Joe, what about the kids?"</i>

02:03.082 --> 02:04.541
What can we do

02:04.626 --> 02:08.045
<i>to keep our kids healthy</i>
<i>and fight childhood obesity?</i>

02:08.127 --> 02:12.257
Which is a real problem
in just about every country I visited.

02:12.341 --> 02:15.845
What about fruits and veggies?
Do you ever eat fruits and veggies?

02:15.928 --> 02:17.764
<i>Sitting around</i>
<i>chatting to these youngsters</i>

02:17.847 --> 02:19.891
<i>brought back memories</i>
<i>of when I was their age.</i>

02:19.974 --> 02:21.726
<i>Sure, I ate fruits and veggies</i>

02:21.809 --> 02:23.645
<i>when Mum and Dad made us,</i>

02:23.728 --> 02:27.065
<i>but they certainly weren't top of the list</i>
<i>when it came to my favorites.</i>

02:27.147 --> 02:29.984
<i>In fact, they were probably</i>
<i>way down the bottom,</i>

02:30.068 --> 02:32.361
<i>even thought I knew they were good for me.</i>

02:32.444 --> 02:35.948
My favorite food when I was your age...

02:36.032 --> 02:40.160
was ice cream
with chocolate flavoring on top.

02:40.243 --> 02:42.371
<i>And these guys, they were no different. </i>

02:42.454 --> 02:44.916
My favorite food is donuts.

02:44.999 --> 02:47.960
Dumplings, and... I like pizza.

02:48.044 --> 02:49.962
-Pizza.
-Cheesecake.

02:50.046 --> 02:51.881
Chicken fingers and ice cream.

02:51.964 --> 02:54.050
-Ice cream.
-Ice cream.

02:54.133 --> 02:55.509
[Joe Cross]
<i>And it got me thinking.</i>

02:55.592 --> 02:57.136
<i>If I knew back then</i>

02:57.219 --> 03:00.014
<i>that fruits and vegetables</i>
<i>made me healthy and strong,</i>

03:00.098 --> 03:02.725
<i>why did I struggle to eat them?</i>

03:02.809 --> 03:06.854
<i>And I'm pretty sure the same could be said</i>
<i>for millions of other people.</i>

03:06.938 --> 03:08.563
Why did you choose this?

03:08.647 --> 03:10.775
Well, because I'm lazy, and it looks good.

03:10.858 --> 03:13.778
<i>But contrary to what</i>
<i>we're told in the media,</i>

03:13.861 --> 03:16.864
<i>obesity itself isn't the main problem.</i>

03:16.948 --> 03:19.658
<i>It's all the diseases</i>
<i>which become more commonplace</i>

03:19.742 --> 03:22.411
<i>when living at an unhealthy weight.</i>

03:22.494 --> 03:24.956
But in order to deal
with childhood obesity

03:25.039 --> 03:26.916
and the downstream effects,

03:26.999 --> 03:29.376
we need to understand the root cause.

03:29.459 --> 03:31.129
<i>After talking to some experts,</i>

03:31.211 --> 03:34.966
it became clear to me
that this problem is three-fold.

03:35.049 --> 03:38.301
<i>Lack of knowledge </i>
<i>of what healthy foods are</i>

03:38.385 --> 03:39.762
<i>and how to prepare them,</i>

03:39.846 --> 03:43.473
<i>lack of access to healthy</i>
<i>and affordable options,</i>

03:43.557 --> 03:45.852
<i>ranging from food deserts in inner cities</i>

03:45.935 --> 03:48.311
<i>to poor school lunch programs,</i>

03:48.395 --> 03:50.940
and the impact of negative role models,

03:51.023 --> 03:54.026
when a parent, a teacher,
or even a celebrity

03:54.110 --> 03:55.903
<i>demonstrates unhealthy behavior.</i>

03:55.987 --> 03:59.364
I pretty much just take a handful of them
like... [gobbles]

03:59.448 --> 04:03.202
[Cross] <i>How can kids today break the cycle</i>
<i>of poor eating habits</i>

04:03.285 --> 04:06.038
<i>that started perhaps a generation ago?</i>

04:06.122 --> 04:09.458
<i>Because I reckon</i>
<i>that if I'd followed a healthier path</i>

04:09.541 --> 04:10.877
<i>ever since I was a kid,</i>

04:10.960 --> 04:14.337
<i>things would have been</i>
<i>completely different for me.</i>

04:14.421 --> 04:18.257
<i>I might not have become</i>
<i>fat, sick, and nearly dead.</i>

04:18.341 --> 04:19.301
<i>And looking back,</i>

04:19.384 --> 04:22.554
<i>boy, I would have loved</i>
<i>to avoid that version of me,</i>

04:22.637 --> 04:25.640
<i>the one that suffered </i>
<i>through pain, unhappiness,</i>

04:25.724 --> 04:28.310
<i>and years of taking medication.</i>

04:28.393 --> 04:31.022
So I decided to try
and figure out how everyone,

04:31.105 --> 04:33.356
<i>teachers, parents, kids,</i>

04:33.440 --> 04:36.778
can come together
and overcome these obstacles.

04:37.736 --> 04:39.781
Where do all the fruits
and vegetables come from?

04:41.032 --> 04:43.700
Uh, gardens.

04:43.785 --> 04:45.368
Gardens where?

04:45.452 --> 04:50.166
Up in countries like, um, the Catskills.

04:50.249 --> 04:53.752
Do you think it's possible
to grow vegetables

04:53.836 --> 04:55.922
on the rooftop of your house?

04:56.005 --> 04:58.507
[scoffs]
I would not like doing that,

04:58.590 --> 05:01.718
because it's pretty dangerous
growing vegetables,

05:01.803 --> 05:05.014
-and I don't have as many plants up there.
-Right.

05:10.895 --> 05:14.816
[Cross] <i>Despite Julian's trepidation </i>
<i>about the dangers of rooftop farming,</i>

05:14.899 --> 05:17.985
<i>some people actually enjoy</i>
<i>growing vegetables up there.</i>

05:18.069 --> 05:22.447
<i>Today I found myself in Brooklyn</i>
<i>at the Eagle Street rooftop farm,</i>

05:22.531 --> 05:23.448
<i>which was a pioneer </i>

05:23.532 --> 05:26.451
<i>in bringing fresh fruits, and vegetables, </i>
<i>and even eggs</i>

05:26.535 --> 05:29.538
<i>to their urban neighbors</i>
<i>who might not otherwise have access</i>

05:29.621 --> 05:32.457
<i>to that kind of fresh, whole food.</i>

05:32.541 --> 05:34.961
<i>While here, I met up with Sam Kass,</i>

05:35.044 --> 05:37.796
<i>one of the country's </i>
<i>leading nutrition experts.</i>

05:37.880 --> 05:40.590
<i>I figured since he spent</i>
<i>the last several years</i>

05:40.674 --> 05:44.136
<i>as the senior nutrition policy advisor</i>
<i>to President Obama,</i>

05:44.220 --> 05:45.972
<i>cooking in the White House kitchen,</i>

05:46.055 --> 05:49.808
<i>and as executive director</i>
<i>of the First Lady's Let's Move initiative,</i>

05:49.892 --> 05:53.062
<i>he might know a thing or two</i>
<i>about where this country is going</i>

05:53.145 --> 05:55.438
<i>when it comes to raising healthy kids.</i>

05:55.522 --> 05:57.066
So, who likes melons?

05:57.149 --> 05:58.234
[cheering]

05:58.317 --> 06:00.443
Nice! Melons are super-good for you.

06:00.527 --> 06:01.863
They keep your tummy all happy.

06:03.072 --> 06:05.199
[Cross]
<i>So, Sam, working in the White House,</i>

06:05.283 --> 06:07.534
from an outsider's point of view,
it looks like a place

06:07.617 --> 06:11.122
where lots of problems come
to try and get solved, right?

06:11.205 --> 06:16.127
<i>How big is the problem, you think,</i>
<i>with what we're all eating?</i>

06:16.210 --> 06:19.005
[Sam Kass] <i>I'd say there are few problems </i>
<i>that are bigger.</i>

06:19.088 --> 06:20.172
Everything is at stake,

06:20.256 --> 06:23.968
our kids' ability to learn,
our healthcare system, our economy.

06:24.051 --> 06:26.971
There are huge costs
when it comes to the issues around health.

06:27.054 --> 06:30.349
<i>Our diet is a huge cause</i>
<i>of preventable death and disease</i>

06:30.432 --> 06:31.350
<i>in this country.</i>

06:31.433 --> 06:33.768
<i>We have to fundamentally shift</i>
<i>what we're eating</i>

06:33.852 --> 06:35.146
<i>and what we're giving to our kids</i>

06:35.229 --> 06:37.647
<i>if we wanna really see</i>
<i>the prosperous future</i>

06:37.731 --> 06:40.318
that we all, you know,
know that our kids deserve.

06:40.400 --> 06:44.571
Right now, kids are seeing
5,500 ads a year for junk food

06:44.654 --> 06:47.782
and about 100 ads
for fruits, vegetables, and whole grains.

06:47.866 --> 06:49.451
[Cross]
<i>There's an imbalance there, isn't there?</i>

06:49.534 --> 06:50.369
[Kass] <i>A huge imbalance.</i>

06:50.452 --> 06:52.997
<i>An so long as that's the case,</i>
<i>we're not gonna be very successful.</i>

06:53.080 --> 06:55.124
<i>We're not gonna get kids</i>
<i>to want to eat fruits and vegetables.</i>

06:55.207 --> 06:56.042
[Announcer]
<i>Baconator!</i>

06:56.125 --> 06:58.210
[Kass]
<i>They respond to celebrity.</i>

06:58.294 --> 07:00.296
<i>They respond</i>
<i>to the, you know, cartoon characters</i>

07:00.379 --> 07:03.174
<i>on the sugary cereals,</i>
<i>or the candy, or whatever.</i>

07:03.257 --> 07:04.716
They're great!

07:04.799 --> 07:06.801
[Kass]
<i>I think part of what we have to do</i>

07:06.885 --> 07:10.056
is take the power
of characters and marketing

07:10.139 --> 07:11.431
and put it towards healthier foods.

07:11.514 --> 07:13.976
Captain Vegetable!

07:16.062 --> 07:18.605
Oh, Captain Vegetable?

07:18.688 --> 07:19.814
Right now, we have a problem.

07:19.898 --> 07:23.277
The loudest voices in this space
are critics, not leaders.

07:23.361 --> 07:26.948
The First Lady getting a new complaint
about her school lunch program.

07:27.031 --> 07:29.783
This time,
from a second grader in Louisiana.

07:35.289 --> 07:38.833
Who should be making
the decisions what you eat,

07:38.917 --> 07:40.502
and school choice, and everything else?

07:40.585 --> 07:42.545
[Kass] <i>Doom and gloom, we know that sells.</i>

07:42.629 --> 07:44.215
But actually, what we need is solutions.

07:44.298 --> 07:46.258
And we're seeing people at every level,

07:46.342 --> 07:48.760
from the White House to pre-schoolers,

07:48.843 --> 07:51.305
uh, taking action,
and really changing their communities,

07:51.389 --> 07:52.390
and changing people's lives.

07:52.472 --> 07:53.975
And that's what this is all about.

08:12.742 --> 08:14.286
<i>My name is Eliza Fournier.</i>

08:14.370 --> 08:16.247
<i>I am the Urban Youth Programs Director</i>

08:16.330 --> 08:19.250
for the Chicago Botanic Garden
Windy City Harvest program.

08:19.333 --> 08:22.003
And started out
as creating school gardens,

08:22.086 --> 08:25.839
um, for schools in the Chicago
Public School system and beyond.

08:25.922 --> 08:27.133
And what we were noticing is

08:27.216 --> 08:30.552
kids were really excited
about the planting day

08:30.635 --> 08:32.636
and the before and after,
and parents were too.

08:32.721 --> 08:35.932
<i>So, we really wanted</i>
<i>a chance to stick around</i>

08:36.017 --> 08:38.684
and see what happened next.

08:38.768 --> 08:43.024
Um, did this make a difference
in how they viewed the environment?

08:43.107 --> 08:45.317
Did this make a difference
in their lifestyle?

08:45.401 --> 08:47.319
<i>The farms were really a great way</i>

08:47.403 --> 08:50.322
to do a youth development program
around horticulture

08:50.406 --> 08:52.866
in a way that really related to everyone.

08:52.949 --> 08:54.118
Everyone eats food,

08:54.201 --> 08:56.203
and so everyone can get excited
about seeing how it's grown,

08:56.287 --> 08:57.620
because it's super-miraculous.

08:57.704 --> 09:01.167
At first, it was really hard
to get kids to wanna do this.

09:01.250 --> 09:02.751
It was like,
"Where are gonna get these kids?

09:02.834 --> 09:06.088
How are we gonna tell them
it's okay, it's cool, it's fun?"

09:06.172 --> 09:08.090
But now that we've been around
for 10 years,

09:08.174 --> 09:09.632
<i>now, it's word of mouth.</i>

09:09.716 --> 09:13.845
I tried to get so many people to come.
Like, but they didn't wanna go.

09:13.928 --> 09:17.475
Like, I told them this is
a very good experience for everybody,

09:17.557 --> 09:19.268
but they don't believe me, so...

09:19.351 --> 09:20.519
They missing out.

09:20.602 --> 09:22.313
I love this.

09:22.396 --> 09:25.316
It wasn't what I expected,

09:25.399 --> 09:26.317
the green and all that.

09:26.400 --> 09:28.486
I didn't think I was gonna like it,
but it's real nice.

09:29.320 --> 09:31.821
It changed me as a person.

09:31.905 --> 09:33.615
And it help me with, um...

09:33.698 --> 09:34.824
I have anxiety,

09:34.908 --> 09:36.327
and it's really helped me with that.

09:36.410 --> 09:39.121
'Cause now,
I can talk to people with eye contact.

09:39.205 --> 09:40.997
You know, I used
to get sweaty and nervous.

09:41.082 --> 09:42.791
Now, I'm good.

09:42.874 --> 09:46.128
[Fournier] <i>So, seeing how food grows</i>
<i>has been the biggest change.</i>

09:47.171 --> 09:49.381
It just blows teenagers' minds.

09:49.465 --> 09:51.633
It blows everybody's minds.
I mean, it's beautiful.

09:51.716 --> 09:53.802
<i>And those kids who were like,</i>
<i>"I would never eat that.</i>

09:53.885 --> 09:57.098
It's in the dirt, and that's weird,
and I don't eat green things."

09:57.181 --> 10:00.434
<i>And then once they've seen it growing,</i>
<i>how it tastes...</i>

10:00.518 --> 10:02.894
<i>A lot of kids come in not liking tomatoes,</i>

10:02.977 --> 10:04.646
and then they tasted
sun gold cherry tomato,

10:04.729 --> 10:06.524
and they're like,
"What? This isn't a tomato!

10:06.606 --> 10:08.024
What are you giving me?"

10:08.109 --> 10:09.485
And it's totally a tomato,

10:09.568 --> 10:11.445
and then they're converts for life.

10:11.529 --> 10:14.739
When they've planted it themselves,
harvested it, cared for it,

10:14.823 --> 10:16.783
<i>they're much more willing to eat it.</i>

10:17.784 --> 10:20.246
[Kid] <i>In the beginning, I seen </i>
<i>how it was growing out of the ground,</i>

10:20.329 --> 10:21.205
<i>and how it tastes,</i>

10:21.288 --> 10:23.207
and I'm like,
"I'm really not gonna eat that."

10:23.290 --> 10:25.584
But as it kept going on,

10:25.667 --> 10:29.087
part of us working here
was tasting the food.

10:29.171 --> 10:31.257
Part of us working was trying new things.

10:31.340 --> 10:34.759
So, I ended up trying the kale,
swiss chard.

10:34.843 --> 10:37.637
I tried the tomatoes.

10:37.720 --> 10:40.182
There was a lot of stuff
I just tried for the first time,

10:40.266 --> 10:41.350
and I ended up liking it.

10:41.433 --> 10:43.768
I eat green tomatoes, carrots...

10:44.853 --> 10:48.190
spinach, basil, leeks,

10:48.274 --> 10:51.025
and... watermelon,

10:51.109 --> 10:53.695
and swiss chard.

10:53.778 --> 10:55.531
[Director] Did you eat
any of that stuff before?

10:55.614 --> 10:56.656
No.

10:58.741 --> 10:59.784
No.

11:00.785 --> 11:02.329
It was nasty.

11:03.663 --> 11:05.957
[Director] Is your family eating
a little bit differently too?

11:06.040 --> 11:07.626
-Yeah.
-[Director] Because of you?

11:08.710 --> 11:10.462
I teach them to eat right.

11:10.546 --> 11:12.964
Me of anyone
should be living out these principles

11:13.047 --> 11:14.592
and feeding my kids in this way.

11:14.674 --> 11:16.302
And I use it as an excuse all the time.

11:16.385 --> 11:18.803
'Well, my kids wouldn't eat that.
My kids don't wanna try that.

11:18.887 --> 11:20.805
That would be weird to my kids."

11:20.889 --> 11:24.393
<i>But they oftentimes prove me wrong</i>
<i>time and time again.</i>

11:24.476 --> 11:27.396
<i>So, that's true with all of our families.</i>

11:27.479 --> 11:29.523
<i>It totally comes from the kids.</i>

11:29.607 --> 11:31.816
<i>Because parents, we have this idea...</i>

11:31.900 --> 11:33.735
I don't know what we're trying
to protect our kids from.

11:33.818 --> 11:35.487
These healthy vegetables.

11:35.571 --> 11:39.575
But we feel like, "Ah, they won't eat it,
so I'm not even gonna try."

11:41.117 --> 11:45.456
<i>It takes a kid to say, "I want it,</i>
<i>and you should eat it too."</i>

11:45.539 --> 11:48.875
And then that's the circle, the click...

11:48.958 --> 11:51.044
The a-ha moment is had.

11:52.463 --> 11:54.465
[school bell ringing]

11:57.676 --> 11:59.428
[Kate Corcoran]
<i>March is National Nutrition Month,</i>

11:59.511 --> 12:02.847
<i>and it's the best place to springboard</i>
<i>this information for the kids.</i>

12:02.931 --> 12:04.225
<i>We're getting ready for spring.</i>

12:04.308 --> 12:08.019
<i>They sort of have a voracious appetite</i>
<i>for something new</i>

12:08.102 --> 12:09.938
after coming off of the winter,

12:10.021 --> 12:11.398
and they really absorb

12:11.482 --> 12:13.900
all of the information that I give them
like a sponge.

12:13.983 --> 12:17.279
"So, you wanna learn about nutrition?
Keep reading to accomplish that."

12:18.614 --> 12:20.491
"This month is all about nutrition.

12:20.574 --> 12:21.659
I mean, did you ever realize

12:21.741 --> 12:24.953
that one out of three people
will have diabetes in 2050?

12:25.036 --> 12:25.995
Crazy, right?"

12:26.079 --> 12:29.541
"Did you know the first...
The number one killer of America?

12:29.625 --> 12:30.709
Well, it's food.

12:30.792 --> 12:32.877
The killer is heart attack, diabetes.

12:32.961 --> 12:35.838
Not murder. That's down
at the bottom of the list.

12:35.922 --> 12:37.591
You might be thinking, 'What?'"

12:37.675 --> 12:39.551
"So, you better get a membership
at the gym

12:39.635 --> 12:41.052
or make some room in your fridge,

12:41.135 --> 12:44.556
because pretty soon, your fridge
will be filled with fruits and veggies."

12:44.640 --> 12:46.057
[Corcoran]
<i>Why would we not want</i>

12:46.140 --> 12:49.395
<i>the 60% or more processed foods</i>
<i>in our daily diet,</i>

12:49.478 --> 12:51.397
day after day after day?

12:51.480 --> 12:53.106
What's the issue with that?

12:53.189 --> 12:54.525
[Corcoran speaking]

12:54.608 --> 12:55.442
What's gonna happen?

12:57.902 --> 12:59.070
[Corcoran]
Yeah, it's gonna happen.

12:59.153 --> 13:01.197
Where would you want food to come from?

13:01.282 --> 13:02.700
Like, where do you want your food sources?

13:02.782 --> 13:04.660
What are we looking for here? Tyler?

13:04.743 --> 13:06.828
You want it to come
straight from the earth or a tree.

13:06.911 --> 13:08.037
Give me some examples

13:08.121 --> 13:09.914
of food that might be
straight from the earth.

13:09.998 --> 13:11.916
Lettuce.

13:12.000 --> 13:14.043
What kinds of lettuces
are we talking about here?

13:14.127 --> 13:15.878
What kinds of lettuces
are really going to give us

13:15.962 --> 13:18.674
our greatest micronutrient blasts?

13:18.757 --> 13:20.509
Romaine.

13:20.592 --> 13:22.344
Hannah, romaine is a nice one. Yeah?

13:22.428 --> 13:24.137
-Kale.
-Kale, of course.

13:24.220 --> 13:26.640
So using what you've learned,

13:26.724 --> 13:28.975
what would you eat in an entire day,

13:29.058 --> 13:33.146
10 items, that really fit
the ideal healthy plate...

13:34.315 --> 13:36.692
as opposed to...

13:36.775 --> 13:40.362
what most Americans have on their plate
every single day?

13:40.446 --> 13:42.238
-Are you guys ready for this?
-[All] Yeah.

13:42.323 --> 13:45.199
[Corcoran] All right, off you go.
I can't wait to see your projects.

13:46.242 --> 13:50.163
[Cross] <i>So Miss Corcoran's class set out </i>
<i>to list a health day's worth of meals.</i>

13:50.246 --> 13:52.416
<i>Nutrition lessons aren't a part</i>

13:52.499 --> 13:54.959
<i>of Miss C's standard, </i>
<i>fifth grade curriculum,</i>

13:55.043 --> 13:56.587
<i>but she sneaks it in</i>

13:56.670 --> 14:00.382
<i>by building her requisite lessons</i>
<i>around nutrition topics.</i>

