<i>Today's class is about percentages,</i>

14:02.634 --> 14:06.304
<i>so the assignment is</i>
<i>to list 10 food items for the day,</i>

14:06.388 --> 14:10.016
<i>each representing 10%</i>
<i>of the daily food intake</i>

14:10.099 --> 14:14.396
<i>with a goal of 60%</i>
<i>being unprocessed or whole foods.</i>

14:14.480 --> 14:18.609
<i>Basically, it's a math lesson</i>
<i>with a little nutrition mixed in.</i>

14:18.692 --> 14:19.942
What are you calling your day?

14:20.026 --> 14:21.362
Micronutrient madness.

14:21.445 --> 14:22.278
I love that.

14:22.363 --> 14:26.282
[Cross] <i>Kate's nutrition lessons</i>
<i>include the idea of smart swaps.</i>

14:26.367 --> 14:29.578
<i>This is a great chance for her class </i>
<i>to think about times in the day</i>

14:29.661 --> 14:33.749
<i>when a piece of fruit or vegetable </i>
<i>could replace a processed snack food.</i>

14:33.832 --> 14:36.167
All right, so, let's just think
for a second here.

14:36.250 --> 14:37.919
Two plus three is what?

14:39.212 --> 14:40.046
Five.

14:40.129 --> 14:41.632
-Plus one is...
-Six.

14:41.715 --> 14:44.926
So, that's like 60% of your food.

14:45.009 --> 14:46.637
I think we're missing four items.

14:46.720 --> 14:49.723
So we have to figure out
where you might put those.

14:49.807 --> 14:51.433
You go ahead and look over that

14:51.517 --> 14:54.770
and think about what
those other four items might possibly be.

14:54.853 --> 14:57.105
Like, where do you think
you might put pancakes?

14:58.356 --> 15:00.024
It's really...

15:00.108 --> 15:01.777
[Corcoran] <i>When you list out</i>
<i>what you eat in a day,</i>

15:01.860 --> 15:04.028
<i>look at a kid,</i>
<i>they have pancakes for breakfast.</i>

15:04.112 --> 15:06.239
<i>They come into school,</i>
<i>they've got fishies for a snack.</i>

15:06.322 --> 15:07.741
<i>And then lunch comes along,</i>

15:07.825 --> 15:09.785
<i>and it's the macaroni and cheese, </i>
<i>the tater tots,</i>

15:09.868 --> 15:11.537
<i>the ham, and the butter, and the bagel.</i>

15:11.620 --> 15:14.330
<i>And then they go home from school,</i>
<i>and it's Pop-Tarts in a package.</i>

15:14.415 --> 15:18.126
<i>And then for dinner,</i>
<i>maybe a delicious lasagna was cooked,</i>

15:18.209 --> 15:19.878
<i>and that sounds fantastic.</i>

15:19.961 --> 15:22.296
<i>But you look</i>
<i>at all of those items in a day,</i>

15:22.380 --> 15:23.799
<i>and you think, "Oh, my god!</i>

15:23.882 --> 15:26.802
<i>90% of what I've eaten in a day </i>
<i>is processed foods."</i>

15:26.885 --> 15:29.638
<i>But, you know,</i>
<i>this is happening every single day,</i>

15:29.721 --> 15:32.390
<i>day after day, </i>
<i>for the majority of these kids.</i>

15:34.476 --> 15:38.605
<i>So, I think for them to write down </i>
<i>in a food journal what you're eating,</i>

15:38.689 --> 15:41.190
<i>and see it before your eyes,</i>
<i>and face the truth that,</i>

15:41.274 --> 15:42.984
"If I continue like this,

15:43.067 --> 15:46.154
I could end up being
potentially very sick someday.

15:46.237 --> 15:49.533
<i>So, maybe instead of those Goldfish,</i>
<i>I'm gonna put in an orange.</i>

15:49.616 --> 15:51.827
<i>Or maybe instead of those Pop-Tarts</i>
<i>when I go home,</i>

15:51.910 --> 15:54.287
<i>I'm gonna grab the celery and the hummus."</i>

15:54.370 --> 15:56.832
Guys, some kids wanted to know
how to spell "quinoa."

15:56.915 --> 16:00.627
[Corcoran] <i>So I've noticed </i>
<i>that they're trying to swap out,</i>

16:00.711 --> 16:02.336
<i>implement some of the ideas,</i>

16:02.420 --> 16:03.630
but it's hard. It's really hard.

16:04.673 --> 16:07.049
<i>Why can't we have cooking classes</i>
<i>in elementary school</i>

16:07.133 --> 16:10.094
<i>that teach kids how to make</i>
<i>a really great, seasonal, healthy meal</i>

16:10.178 --> 16:13.014
<i>based on items you might buy</i>
<i>around the perimeter?</i>

16:14.683 --> 16:17.101
[Cross] <i>Kate's healthy eating lessons </i>
<i>got me thinking.</i>

16:17.185 --> 16:21.523
<i>Not every food in every meal</i>
<i>can be whole foods,</i>

16:21.607 --> 16:26.068
<i>but what if kids and adults</i>
<i>would make some of Kate's smart swaps?</i>

16:27.028 --> 16:29.113
<i>Let's take her daily food diary,</i>

16:29.197 --> 16:31.700
<i>and swap out the fishies for an apple</i>

16:31.783 --> 16:34.953
<i>and the Pop-Tars</i>
<i>with some celery and hummus,</i>

16:35.036 --> 16:38.874
<i>and maybe add in some leafy greens</i>
<i>instead of the tater tots.</i>

16:38.957 --> 16:40.208
<i>What does that look like?</i>

16:40.291 --> 16:42.628
<i>Well, apart from being</i>
<i>a lot more colorful,</i>

16:42.711 --> 16:44.630
<i>I reckon it's a lot better.</i>

16:46.339 --> 16:49.510
So, we know that a child
with one obese parent

16:49.593 --> 16:51.302
is 40% more likely to be obese,

16:51.385 --> 16:54.515
and two obese parents
is 80% more likely to be obese.

16:54.598 --> 16:57.350
So parents are...
couldn't be more important

16:57.433 --> 16:59.686
in ensuring our kids get off
to a healthy start.

16:59.770 --> 17:01.647
So this starts
when they're very, very young,

17:01.730 --> 17:03.941
making sure they're getting
lots of fruits and vegetables,

17:04.022 --> 17:07.944
<i>because it's shaping how our kids taste</i>
<i>and what their taste preferences are.</i>

17:08.027 --> 17:09.695
Oh, my goodness! Look at that.

17:09.780 --> 17:11.990
Aw! A little cute one.

17:12.907 --> 17:14.367
[Kass]
<i>Parents have to lead by example.</i>

17:14.450 --> 17:16.035
<i>And I think </i>
<i>one of the key things they can do,</i>

17:16.117 --> 17:17.829
<i>which is really undervalued,</i>

17:17.913 --> 17:20.248
<i>is how you set up your home</i>
<i>for kids to make decisions.</i>

17:20.330 --> 17:22.250
If there's water
as opposed to sugary drinks,

17:22.333 --> 17:23.710
that's what your kids are gonna drink,

17:23.794 --> 17:25.294
-and that just becomes what they know.
-Yeah.

17:25.377 --> 17:27.338
And I think parents also have
to do that too.

17:27.421 --> 17:29.215
<i>You can't have the kid,</i>
<i>and force them to drink water,</i>

17:29.298 --> 17:30.759
<i>and you're sitting there drinking a soda.</i>

17:30.842 --> 17:34.303
<i>So, I think that kind of leadership </i>
<i>in the home is absolutely vital,</i>

17:34.387 --> 17:36.430
<i>and something that we can do</i>
<i>which costs nothing.</i>

17:36.514 --> 17:39.433
<i>It just means what are you putting out?</i>
<i>What do your kids see?</i>

17:39.517 --> 17:40.978
Because that's what they're gonna eat.

17:44.731 --> 17:48.986
[Cross] <i>A lot of parents really struggle</i>
<i>to get their kids to eat healthier meals.</i>

17:49.068 --> 17:50.528
Where's Lieve-ster?

17:50.612 --> 17:52.739
[Cross]
<i>Enter Dr. Brian Wansink...</i>

17:52.823 --> 17:54.783
Lieve! [screams]

17:55.951 --> 17:57.493
Lieve!

17:57.578 --> 17:59.788
[Cross]
<i>A professor at Cornell University</i>

17:59.871 --> 18:03.291
<i>who focuses on human behavior</i>
<i>when it comes to food.</i>

18:03.374 --> 18:04.500
Hi. Hi.

18:04.585 --> 18:09.006
[Cross] <i>He's put his research from </i>
<i>the nutrition lab to the test at home.</i>

18:09.088 --> 18:12.174
<i>Let's see</i>
<i>if his three daughters pass the test.</i>

18:14.011 --> 18:16.095
[Dr. Wansink]
<i>So, we've talked to hundreds of parents.</i>

18:16.178 --> 18:17.430
<i>We find that most parents say,</i>

18:17.513 --> 18:19.766
<i>"You know, I can't control </i>
<i>what my kids eat."</i>

18:19.850 --> 18:21.059
<i>And they're correct.</i>

18:21.142 --> 18:23.937
<i>Nobody can control 100%</i>
<i>of what your kids do.</i>

18:24.021 --> 18:26.522
<i>But what we've found</i>
<i>is that the person in the household</i>

18:26.607 --> 18:30.027
who purchases
and prepares most of the food

18:30.109 --> 18:35.699
can control about 72%
of what their kids eat.

18:35.782 --> 18:36.700
But the thing is

18:36.783 --> 18:38.660
it's either for the better
or for the worse.

18:38.744 --> 18:40.328
It's for the better
if you've got a fruit bowl.

18:40.411 --> 18:42.288
It's for the worse
if you have a cookie dish.

18:42.371 --> 18:43.247
It's for the better

18:43.331 --> 18:45.458
if you go to a restaurant
that actually serves salad.

18:45.541 --> 18:47.836
Versus if you go to a place
that only serves cheesy fries.

18:47.919 --> 18:49.337
A while back,
somebody came to me and said,

18:49.420 --> 18:53.174
"What can we do
to get our kids to pick the right thing

18:53.257 --> 18:54.425
<i>when we go out for fast food?"</i>

18:54.508 --> 18:57.136
<i>'Cause for most parents,</i>
<i>fast food is a reality.</i>

18:57.219 --> 18:59.472
<i>I don't wanna cook sometimes.</i>

18:59.555 --> 19:00.682
<i>But what do you do to get them</i>

19:00.766 --> 19:03.142
to take the apple slices
instead of the French fries?

19:03.225 --> 19:05.020
Well, you can't say,

19:05.103 --> 19:06.604
"Which is most healthy?"

19:06.688 --> 19:07.856
'Cause they don't care.

19:07.939 --> 19:09.691
They're still gonna
choose the French fries.

19:09.775 --> 19:11.317
But what we found you can do...

19:11.400 --> 19:13.111
if you take a kid

19:13.194 --> 19:15.822
and have him think about things
from another person's perspective,

19:15.906 --> 19:19.492
you can interrupt their script
of just saying,

19:19.575 --> 19:21.995
<i>"I want French fries. I want French fries.</i>
<i>I want French fries."</i>

19:22.079 --> 19:24.413
<i>So we did this study a while back</i>
<i>where we asked people,</i>

19:24.497 --> 19:27.709
"What would Batman eat,
French fries or apple slices?"

19:27.793 --> 19:29.127
And the kid would answer.

19:29.210 --> 19:32.798
Then we'd say, "What do you want,
French fries or apple slices?"

19:32.881 --> 19:33.757
And what happened

19:33.840 --> 19:36.634
the percentage of kids
who asked for apple slices

19:36.718 --> 19:39.220
went up from 5% to 50%.

19:39.303 --> 19:41.555
But it didn't even matter who we used.

19:41.639 --> 19:43.182
We'd say, "Who's your favorite teacher?"

19:43.265 --> 19:45.018
All we had to do was force them

19:45.102 --> 19:48.187
to take somebody else's point of view
for a second,

19:48.270 --> 19:50.065
and it... almost rewired them.

19:50.148 --> 19:52.067
Okay, boys and girls,

19:52.150 --> 19:55.862
what do you think I eat
that helps keep me healthy and strong,

19:55.946 --> 19:58.656
French fries or apples?

19:58.740 --> 20:00.408
[Kids]
We think apples.

20:00.491 --> 20:04.370
That's right. I'm an apple kind of guy.

20:04.453 --> 20:07.958
But all fruits and vegetables
help keep me and you healthy.

20:08.041 --> 20:11.086
So, load up on your fruits
and veggies, kids.

20:11.169 --> 20:14.422
[Kids]
Now, we want apples! Yay!

20:17.675 --> 20:20.971
Okay, so, guys, you've just come back
from getting some food.

20:21.054 --> 20:24.515
Now, you've come back, Lieve,
with a banana

20:24.598 --> 20:26.768
that you're impersonating as a smile.

20:26.852 --> 20:29.062
And Audrey and Valerie
have come back with apples.

20:29.146 --> 20:33.900
Now, is this only because I'm here
that you're getting this,

20:33.984 --> 20:37.528
or what do you normally have
when you come home from school?

20:37.611 --> 20:39.740
-Fruit.
-What sort of fruit do you have?

20:40.656 --> 20:44.243
Banana, or... orange maybe,

20:44.326 --> 20:45.912
or some grapes.

20:45.996 --> 20:50.458
So what about cookies,
and chocolate, and milkshakes, and...

20:50.541 --> 20:52.878
-Does that not happen here at home?
-No.

20:52.961 --> 20:54.796
My mom doesn't make that for us.

20:55.756 --> 20:57.132
-Never?
-No, never.

20:57.215 --> 20:58.759
She makes us smoothies.

20:58.842 --> 21:00.468
So, smoothies. So, what's in...

21:00.551 --> 21:03.221
Out of strawberries or blueberries.

21:03.304 --> 21:04.388
Right, okay.

21:04.472 --> 21:07.349
-So, do you guys like cookies?
-Mm-hmm.

21:07.433 --> 21:10.603
I eat every single sweet stuff
in the world.

21:10.686 --> 21:13.522
You eat every single sweet in the world?

21:13.606 --> 21:16.985
So, Brian, how much focus,
how much thought

21:17.068 --> 21:19.029
do you put into teaching

21:19.112 --> 21:22.406
when it comes to food choices,
nutrition for your kids?

21:22.490 --> 21:24.826
I put very little effort in doing that,

21:24.910 --> 21:26.036
because what I realized is

21:26.119 --> 21:29.330
that it's not necessarily
teaching them about nutrition.

21:29.413 --> 21:31.875
It's just essentially modeling
the right sort of behavior.

21:31.958 --> 21:34.335
So, I eat fruit when I come home.

21:34.418 --> 21:35.336
I eat a good breakfast.

21:35.419 --> 21:37.421
So that's actually
what they see as natural.

21:37.505 --> 21:38.799
But I don't lecture them.

21:38.882 --> 21:41.509
I don't think they know
any facts about nutrition.

21:43.178 --> 21:45.013
<i>One of the things</i>
<i>that we found in our research</i>

21:45.096 --> 21:47.974
<i>was that one thing</i>
<i>that's very enticing to kids</i>

21:48.058 --> 21:51.978
<i>ends up being sort of like</i>
<i>attractive packaging and things like this.</i>

21:52.062 --> 21:55.773
<i>But we found that people are less likely</i>
<i>to choose breakfast cereal</i>

21:55.857 --> 21:57.608
<i>when it's not in its original packaging,</i>

21:57.691 --> 21:59.027
<i>because it doesn't look that attractive.</i>

21:59.110 --> 22:01.071
So we have the breakfast cereal which...

22:01.154 --> 22:03.531
There we go. There we go.

22:03.614 --> 22:06.201
It's not really in the attractive,
typically attractive...

22:06.284 --> 22:07.953
You've taken it out of the package.

22:08.036 --> 22:09.162
It doesn't look that...

22:09.246 --> 22:10.663
Does it look that great looking like this?

22:10.746 --> 22:12.748
No, it looks like dog food actually.

22:12.833 --> 22:16.335
And so, how many days a week
do you guys eat breakfast cereal?

22:16.418 --> 22:18.964
-Once.
-Yeah, Audrey, maybe once.

22:19.047 --> 22:21.715
Um, 100 times.

22:21.799 --> 22:24.302
-Okay.
-A hundred times a week?

22:24.385 --> 22:26.595
You were saying before
that you got rid of the bigger bowls?

22:26.679 --> 22:29.850
Yeah, these used to be
the bowls the kids ate out of.

22:29.933 --> 22:33.061
<i>But when we did research,</i>
<i>it showed that a typical kid will pour</i>

22:33.144 --> 22:36.814
<i>about 44% more cereal</i>
<i>in a bigger bowl than a smaller bowl.</i>

22:36.898 --> 22:38.816
Which ones do you guys use all the time?

22:38.900 --> 22:40.026
That one.

22:40.110 --> 22:42.112
Yeah, we don't even use these anymore.

22:42.195 --> 22:44.114
I usually just...

22:44.197 --> 22:47.741
<i>Making food convenient, attractive, </i>
<i>and normal to eat, if it's healthy food,</i>

22:47.825 --> 22:49.743
it guides them more
toward the thing to do.

22:49.827 --> 22:51.370
Thank you guys.

22:51.453 --> 22:53.290
-Give me five.
-Yeah!

22:53.372 --> 22:54.456
Give him a kitty high five.

22:54.540 --> 22:56.542
Kitty high five!

22:56.625 --> 22:58.460
Kitty high five!

23:02.173 --> 23:05.718
[Cross] <i>So, there was a lot of talk</i>
<i>about the problems of kids and obesity. </i>

23:05.801 --> 23:08.554
<i>I wondered what the science said</i>
<i>about that connection.</i>

23:08.637 --> 23:12.558
<i>So, I asked a scientist, </i>
<i>Dr. Janet Wojcicki.</i>

23:12.641 --> 23:13.767
Here's something I wanna know.

23:13.851 --> 23:16.687
What's the problem with being obese?

23:16.770 --> 23:19.857
It's not obesity, per se,
that's the problem.

23:19.941 --> 23:23.485
Obesity is a marker for metabolic disease.

23:23.569 --> 23:26.530
<i>So, it's a marker for increased risk</i>

23:26.614 --> 23:31.328
<i>for type 2 diabetes, for hypertension,</i>
<i>fatty liver disease.</i>

23:31.410 --> 23:35.999
<i>So, not everybody who is obese</i>
<i>is going to be sick,</i>

23:36.082 --> 23:40.461
<i>and not everybody who is lean</i>
<i>is gonna be free from disease,</i>

23:40.544 --> 23:45.383
<i>but obesity is the best marker </i>
<i>that we have for metabolic disease.</i>

23:45.466 --> 23:50.596
Thirty years ago, to see a child
with type 2 diabetes was a rarity.

23:50.679 --> 23:54.725
Whereas now,
to see children with type 2 diabetes

23:54.808 --> 23:56.435
is much, much more common.

23:56.518 --> 23:57.979
So, what's changed, Janet?

23:58.063 --> 23:59.855
[Dr. Wojcicki]
<i>I think for sure the diet.</i>

23:59.940 --> 24:02.984
<i>Because the problem is everywhere we go,</i>

24:03.068 --> 24:06.862
<i>there are so many</i>
<i>sugar-sweetened beverages out there.</i>

24:06.947 --> 24:10.741
<i>The single biggest contributor</i>
<i>to the obesity epidemic </i>

24:10.824 --> 24:13.661
<i>is beverage intake.</i>

24:13.744 --> 24:19.458
What is it about it that makes it so tasty
and makes it so addictive?

24:19.541 --> 24:21.835
I really believe
there's evolutionary reasons.

24:21.919 --> 24:26.465
<i>We're hardwired to crave fats and sugars.</i>

24:26.548 --> 24:31.720
<i>All the fancy marketing and the packages</i>
<i>that make it look great,</i>

24:31.804 --> 24:34.099
<i>unfortunately, the consumer is confused,</i>

24:34.182 --> 24:37.726
<i>and some stuff is labeled </i>
<i>as nutritious, as healthy, health food.</i>

24:39.020 --> 24:40.646
It's tough. I know. I'm a parent as well.

24:40.729 --> 24:42.107
It's very difficult. You're going--

24:42.190 --> 24:44.692
My son asks me,
"Look, it says it has this, Mom."

24:44.775 --> 24:48.821
Or, "I eat that, and it really said
it had vitamin, you know, D."

24:48.904 --> 24:51.074
So, it's hard.

24:51.157 --> 24:55.245
Or then they want the vitamins.
The gummy bears now also.

24:55.328 --> 24:57.247
<i>Even vitamins. You can't escape the sugar.</i>

24:57.330 --> 24:59.915
So we believe that it's really important

25:00.000 --> 25:04.045
children 0 to 5 are developing
eating behaviors for life.

25:04.129 --> 25:05.629
And we're really at a crisis point.

25:05.713 --> 25:07.048
<i>So train your kids.</i>

25:07.132 --> 25:11.802
<i>When they are at a restaurant,</i>
<i>they're thirsty, drink water and milk.</i>

25:11.885 --> 25:13.637
What's the need for anything else?

25:13.721 --> 25:15.432
[Cross]
<i>Well, after that chat,</i>

25:15.514 --> 25:18.517
<i>my mind was racing back</i>
<i>to when I was a kid.</i>

25:19.518 --> 25:21.312
Mom, I'm thirsty.

25:21.396 --> 25:22.980
Have some water, dear.

25:23.064 --> 25:26.151
But, Mom, why can't I have soda?

25:26.234 --> 25:30.030
[Cross] <i>And the constant battle</i>
<i>I used to have with Mum and Dad for soda.</i>

25:30.113 --> 25:32.490
You know water keeps us healthy.

25:32.573 --> 25:36.327
Why don't we add some lemon to yours
to make it taste fresh?

25:36.411 --> 25:38.163
-[doorbell ringing]
-[dog barking]

25:39.788 --> 25:41.291
Who is it?

25:41.374 --> 25:44.169
-It's your great tasting...
-Refreshingly light...

25:44.252 --> 25:46.628
-Disturbingly sweet...
-Delicious...

25:46.712 --> 25:49.174
[All] And cool friends
from the convenience store.

25:49.257 --> 25:50.549
[dog barking]

25:50.632 --> 25:52.801
Thanks, but no thanks.
It's time for you to leave.

25:52.885 --> 25:54.137
Ow!

25:54.220 --> 25:56.097
I think I dropped something.

26:00.268 --> 26:01.643
[Cross]
<i>Say g'day to Deb Grant.</i>

26:01.727 --> 26:02.895
<i>She's a former school teacher</i>

26:02.978 --> 26:06.690
<i>who noticed a growing trend</i>
<i>in overweight and unhealthy teens,</i>

26:06.774 --> 26:09.360
<i>which opened her eyes</i>
<i>to a pervasive problem,</i>

26:09.444 --> 26:12.530
<i>a lack of awareness</i>
<i>of how most of the stuff we eat</i>

26:12.613 --> 26:15.325
<i>is more harmful than a lot of us realize.</i>

26:15.408 --> 26:20.205
[Deb Grant] <i>When I started reading</i>
<i>about food and food choices,</i>

26:20.288 --> 26:22.915
<i>I was shocked</i>
<i>about how much I didn't know.</i>

26:22.998 --> 26:25.126
But I didn't really know
what to do about it,

26:25.210 --> 26:26.211
so I would suggest, you know,

26:26.294 --> 26:28.879
someone should eat a banana
instead of having Doritos,

26:28.962 --> 26:30.756
and usually, I got a lot of eye rolling,

26:30.839 --> 26:32.049
and it didn't go very far.

26:32.133 --> 26:35.178
[Cross] <i>So she put</i>
<i>her thoughts into action</i>

26:35.261 --> 26:37.805
<i>and started the organization FoodFight</i>

26:37.888 --> 26:39.723
<i>as a way to leverage school environments</i>

26:39.807 --> 26:43.602
<i>to educate and empower students</i>
<i>and teachers alike</i>

26:43.685 --> 26:45.646
<i>and give them the resources and knowledge</i>

26:45.729 --> 26:48.690
<i>of how to make healthier choices</i>
<i>for themselves.</i>

26:50.692 --> 26:52.820
[Grant]
<i>I am sure I am not the first person</i>

26:52.903 --> 26:54.780
<i>to stand in front of you and say,</i>

26:54.863 --> 26:57.699
<i>"We are in the midst</i>
<i>of an enormous health crisis."</i>

26:57.783 --> 26:59.993
<i>And I'm sure if I was to ask you</i>

27:00.077 --> 27:07.042
if you know somebody in your family
who is overweight, raise your hand.

27:07.127 --> 27:09.837
Keep it up.
Obesity, raise your other hand.

27:09.920 --> 27:11.548
Heart disease.

27:11.630 --> 27:13.632
-Yeah, raise your foot. Right.
-[laughter]

27:13.715 --> 27:17.094
All right,
all of those lifestyle-related diseases

27:17.178 --> 27:18.471
are connected to what you eat.

27:18.555 --> 27:21.224
And the fact that everybody in this room
is raising their hand

27:21.307 --> 27:23.100
should lead us to understand and believe

27:23.184 --> 27:26.103
that this isn't just her problem
or your problem.

27:26.187 --> 27:27.771
This is a societal issue.

27:27.855 --> 27:31.817
These are sicknesses that are coming
based on what we are putting in our mouths

27:31.900 --> 27:34.862
at lunch, and at breakfast, and at dinner.

27:34.945 --> 27:39.116
If I was to ask you
what do you think are some of the reasons

27:39.200 --> 27:42.077
why we have found ourselves
in that problem...

27:42.162 --> 27:43.829
Anyone wanna-- Yes?

27:43.912 --> 27:45.914
High prices on healthy food.

27:45.998 --> 27:48.418
High prices on healthy food. Absolutely.

27:48.501 --> 27:49.960
That's one. Two?

27:50.043 --> 27:51.546
Some people are depressed.

27:51.629 --> 27:53.381
Some people are depressed.

27:53.464 --> 27:56.301
-And they just eat a lot.
-And so, they overeat. Absolutely.

27:56.384 --> 27:57.885
-What else?
-It's good.

27:57.968 --> 27:58.969
What's good?

27:59.052 --> 28:01.472
-The food that we eat, the unhealthy food.
-The junk food.

28:01.556 --> 28:03.891
The junk food is good, right?

28:03.974 --> 28:08.563
It's comforting, tastes good,
readily available, yeah?

28:08.646 --> 28:13.193
One of the leading culprits
for why that first picture

28:13.318 --> 28:17.405
<i>is how so many people look</i>
<i>walking around today is sugar.</i>

28:17.488 --> 28:21.783
<i>It's about the fact</i>
<i>that we have become sugar addicts.</i>

28:21.867 --> 28:23.494
<i>So I'm gonna put</i>
<i>a couple of drinks up here</i>

28:23.578 --> 28:26.414
<i>that I'm guessing</i>
<i>that some of you are familiar with.</i>

28:27.956 --> 28:30.335
Gatorade. Raise your hand
if you like Gatorade.

28:31.835 --> 28:35.298
<i>Most people don't know,</i>
<i>when they look at sugar grams,</i>

28:35.381 --> 28:37.592
<i>how many teaspoons</i>
<i>of sugar they're consuming.</i>

28:37.675 --> 28:41.178
<i>They have no idea</i>
<i>how you calculate from grams to teaspoons,</i>

28:41.262 --> 28:43.681
<i>that four grams equals one teaspoon.</i>

28:43.764 --> 28:46.267
<i>And so, they look at a label,</i>

28:46.351 --> 28:49.354
<i>and grams exists</i>
<i>completely out of context.</i>

28:51.522 --> 28:53.483
<i>And it's really these light bulb moments,</i>

28:53.566 --> 28:57.570
<i>that notion of, "Oh, if I know</i>
<i>how many teaspoons are in this item,</i>

28:57.654 --> 28:58.820
<i>I can make a choice."</i>

28:58.904 --> 29:01.823
I want you to put these drinks

29:01.907 --> 29:06.246
in order of most sugar to least sugar.

29:06.329 --> 29:08.373
-I think I got this.
-Don't look at the labels.

29:08.456 --> 29:10.667
No looking at the labels.
No, you can't look at the labels.

29:12.918 --> 29:14.962
[Student]
And I think that's it.

29:15.045 --> 29:16.506
[Grant]
Okay, so which is most?

29:17.507 --> 29:19.132
-Coke.
-Okay.

29:19.216 --> 29:20.635
It starts with Coke and then goes down.

29:20.718 --> 29:23.346
Okay, I think he's pretty...
I think he's pretty close.

29:23.429 --> 29:25.222
So, that's-- You're right.

29:25.306 --> 29:28.601
Let's give him a round.
That's good. He got the first one right.

29:28.685 --> 29:32.313
They did not like the sense
that they were being manipulated or played

29:32.397 --> 29:35.023
by the industrial food machinery.

29:35.107 --> 29:37.735
And so they were
much more likely and willing

29:37.818 --> 29:40.821
to kind of engage in conversations
about their diets

29:40.904 --> 29:43.616
once you had defused
this sense of finger wagging

29:43.700 --> 29:46.118
or telling people, you know,

29:46.201 --> 29:48.787
"You're doing a bad job.
You're not making good eating choices."

29:48.870 --> 29:50.415
And then broaden that conversation.

29:50.498 --> 29:52.417
Some of those drinks
I really don't drink a lot.

29:52.500 --> 29:54.209
Probably just the Gatorade.

29:54.294 --> 29:56.337
But that was a surprise,

29:56.421 --> 29:59.590
because every athlete
that you use as a role model,

29:59.674 --> 30:01.049
they're drinking it.

30:01.133 --> 30:02.760
So it makes you wanna drink it,

30:02.843 --> 30:04.679
but you don't notice that
it has that much sugar in it.

30:04.762 --> 30:08.056
It just makes you rethink everything.

30:08.140 --> 30:11.394
When I came home,
I started reading, like, labels.

30:11.477 --> 30:12.936
My mother was like, "What are you doing?"

30:13.020 --> 30:15.315
I'm like, "These people came,

30:15.398 --> 30:18.066
and they talked to us
about sugar and stuff."

30:18.150 --> 30:21.278
And I was like,
"Wow, I was eating a lot of sugar."

30:21.362 --> 30:23.573
And I didn't know
how much sugar I was eating until then.

30:23.656 --> 30:25.575
So, um...

30:26.701 --> 30:28.703
After I was reading everything,

30:28.786 --> 30:31.246
I was like,
"This has a lot, and this doesn't,

30:31.331 --> 30:32.831
so I'm gonna do this instead."

30:32.914 --> 30:34.500
And then, I'm gonna start
drinking more tea

30:34.584 --> 30:37.085
instead of hot chocolate
and stuff like that.

30:37.169 --> 30:38.128
[muttering]
Hot chocolate.

30:38.211 --> 30:39.129
[Producer]
So, that's cool.

30:39.212 --> 30:41.882
What did your mom say
when you told her about that?

30:41.965 --> 30:44.176
I mean, it was
a funny moment for us,

30:44.259 --> 30:48.930
'cause I'm big on sweets.
I love my cakes, my cookies.

30:49.014 --> 30:50.683
I'm big on sweets.

30:50.767 --> 30:55.062
But, um, after that,
I kind of slowed down a little bit.

30:55.145 --> 30:56.313
[Grant]
<i>And it's very exciting</i>

30:56.397 --> 30:59.024
<i>when you see kids realize</i>
<i>how much power they have,</i>

30:59.107 --> 31:03.195
where kids really acknowledge that,
"Wow, we can do something differently.

31:03.278 --> 31:05.072
We don't have to follow that trajectory

31:05.155 --> 31:08.992
and develop diabetes and heart disease
by the time we're 25.

31:09.076 --> 31:10.661
We can have a different future."

31:10.745 --> 31:13.955
<i>It's really lifting them up and saying, </i>
<i>"You have the power to make a difference.</i>

31:14.039 --> 31:17.752
<i>You can vote with your fork.</i>
<i>You can very shortly vote with your vote.</i>

31:17.835 --> 31:21.422
<i>And theres things that you can do.</i>
<i>Let's talk about what those things are."</i>

31:23.800 --> 31:25.551
You guys were great. Thank you.

31:28.388 --> 31:30.515
[Kass]
<i>What I've seen everywhere I've gone,</i>

31:30.598 --> 31:32.933
<i>and in the garden with the First Lady,</i>
<i>and in schools,</i>

31:33.016 --> 31:35.686
that if you just let kids
be a little bit engaged

31:35.770 --> 31:38.230
in the decision making process,
they take ownership.

31:38.313 --> 31:41.776
Be it, let a kid pick out three vegetables
in the grocery store,

31:41.859 --> 31:46.238
or have a child help you cook,
or anything in that realm,

31:46.321 --> 31:47.948
they really take ownership.

31:48.031 --> 31:51.076
And we saw kids stuffing their faces
with raw vegetables

31:51.159 --> 31:53.788
only because they planted it.
No other reason.

31:53.871 --> 31:57.916
And to find those little moments
across a kid's life

31:57.999 --> 32:00.795
that they can have those touches

32:00.878 --> 32:04.632
and feeling of empowerment and ownership,
transormational.

32:07.092 --> 32:08.343
[Cross]
<i>In my previous film,</i>

32:08.428 --> 32:11.388
<i>I had the opportunity to talk </i>
<i>to a wonderful family.</i>

32:11.472 --> 32:13.974
<i>Little Delani and Elise were charmers.</i>

32:14.057 --> 32:16.644
<i>They had an unbelievable story to tell me</i>

32:16.727 --> 32:19.354
<i>of how late one night</i>
<i>after a day of travel,</i>

32:19.439 --> 32:22.315
<i>Mum wanted to stop</i>
<i>at the only place that was open,</i>

32:22.399 --> 32:23.818
<i>a fast food restaurant,</i>

32:23.901 --> 32:25.277
<i>and little Delani said...</i>

32:25.360 --> 32:27.655
I told her, "No, I don't wanna go there,

32:27.738 --> 32:29.657
'cause they have junk food

32:29.740 --> 32:32.242
that, like, it's not good
for you and your body."

32:32.325 --> 32:35.036
We came back from our trip.

32:35.120 --> 32:38.708
It's 11:00 at night.
We'd been traveling on a plane for hours,

32:38.791 --> 32:41.209
and it was the only thing open,
the drive-through,

32:41.293 --> 32:44.254
and they were like,
"Please, don't feed us this food.

32:44.337 --> 32:45.380
Don't feed it to us."

32:45.465 --> 32:50.343
I said, "What about French fries
or a burger? Just a few fries?

32:50.427 --> 32:52.137
Just to have something in your tummy?"

32:52.220 --> 32:56.141
"No, Mommy, we don't want that food.
We learned so many nasty things about it."

32:56.224 --> 32:59.479
It's because of Delani
that I eat healthier.

32:59.562 --> 33:02.940
When she started bringing recipes home
to make a smoothie...

33:03.023 --> 33:06.527
Like, every single day, "Please, Mommy,
buy the ingredients. Please."

33:06.611 --> 33:07.945
To me, that was sort of a sign.

33:08.028 --> 33:10.405
If my four-year-old, at the time,
is coming home

33:10.490 --> 33:13.534
handing me recipes to eat healthier,

33:13.618 --> 33:15.368
I'm gonna do it.

33:15.452 --> 33:16.537
[Cross]
Where did that come from?

33:16.621 --> 33:18.163
It came from my sister.

33:18.246 --> 33:19.540
[Cross]
Oh, really?

33:19.624 --> 33:21.166
Okay, so, now the truth comes out.

33:21.249 --> 33:23.084
[Cross] Do you wanna tell me
what the story was, Elise?

33:23.168 --> 33:25.713
Yeah. I learned it in Wellness.

33:25.796 --> 33:28.966
[Cross] <i>These little girls' attitudes</i>
<i>impressed me so much</i>

33:29.049 --> 33:31.844
<i>that when it came time</i>
<i>to work on this project,</i>

33:31.928 --> 33:33.638
<i>I revisited their story</i>

33:33.721 --> 33:36.139
<i>and learned there was even more to it.</i>

33:36.223 --> 33:39.226
<i>The program</i>
<i>where Elise learned this information</i>

33:39.309 --> 33:42.395
<i>actually began well before Elise's time.</i>

33:42.479 --> 33:44.397
<i>Local teacher, Ginny Reale,</i>

33:44.481 --> 33:48.569
<i>first tried out a Wellness Week</i>
<i>in her classroom back in 2005.</i>

33:48.653 --> 33:51.446
So which color do you think

33:51.531 --> 33:55.952
we should be eating a lot of every day?

33:56.034 --> 33:58.286
Don't tell me purple.

33:58.370 --> 33:59.580
-Green.
-Green. You're right.

33:59.664 --> 34:01.707
[Cross]
<i>This is Ruby and Cailyn.</i>

34:01.791 --> 34:03.584
<i>They were in that first class</i>

34:03.668 --> 34:06.546
<i>when Mrs. Reale began to teach </i>
<i>about wellness.</i>

34:06.629 --> 34:10.215
<i>Now, 23 years old,</i>
<i>Ruby and Cailyn can reflect</i>

34:10.297 --> 34:13.719
<i>on how much of an impact</i>
<i>a teacher can really make.</i>

34:13.803 --> 34:16.346
Mrs. Reale was kind of
rounding up the troops

34:16.429 --> 34:17.974
at East Hampton Middle School.

34:18.056 --> 34:19.809
<i>She started the Wellness Run.</i>

34:19.891 --> 34:22.476
Teaching us more about nutrition,
getting us more active.

34:22.562 --> 34:25.230
<i>And then they brought in</i>
Super Size Me, <i>the documentary,</i>

34:25.313 --> 34:27.107
<i>for the students to watch.</i>

34:27.190 --> 34:29.610
<i>And I personally can remember watching,</i>

34:29.694 --> 34:31.235
<i>and it was just so vivid.</i>

34:31.319 --> 34:33.112
[Morgan Spurlock]
So nasty. [belches]

34:33.196 --> 34:35.866
[Ruby]
<i>What happened to Morgan was so dramatic,</i>

34:35.949 --> 34:37.909
<i>and I remember being like, "Oh, my gosh!</i>

34:37.994 --> 34:39.996
<i>I'm never eating McDonald's again."</i>

34:41.746 --> 34:45.166
[Cross] <i>Ginny was as surprised as anyone</i>
<i>when the first class began</i>

34:45.250 --> 34:49.170
<i>to analyze the nutritional value</i>
<i>of their school lunches,</i>

34:49.254 --> 34:52.592
<i>but no one was surprised</i>
<i>when they came up short.</i>

34:52.675 --> 34:56.469
I felt very confused
by the fact that we were--

34:56.553 --> 34:59.180
Here we were learning
about healthy choices,

34:59.264 --> 35:00.975
and maybe going home
and telling our parents,

35:01.058 --> 35:05.688
"This is what we wanna eat.
We want better food choices."

35:05.771 --> 35:09.942
But that not being translated
into our actual school options.

35:10.026 --> 35:13.445
And so, I think it just
really was a conversation,

35:13.528 --> 35:15.781
and we brought it up
in health class with Ms. Reale.

35:15.865 --> 35:17.867
[Cross]
<i>The kids then came up with a plan</i>

35:17.950 --> 35:22.079
<i>to get the administration to improve</i>
<i>those under-performing school lunches,</i>

35:22.162 --> 35:24.122
<i>a boycott.</i>

35:24.205 --> 35:25.875
[all gasping]

35:25.958 --> 35:28.669
[Ruby] <i>Ms. Reale empowered us</i>
<i>so much with these ideas</i>

35:28.753 --> 35:32.422
<i>that food was important,</i>
<i>and that we could make these decisions.</i>

35:32.505 --> 35:34.717
We were rebelling in a positive way.

35:34.800 --> 35:37.594
[News Anchor]
<i>You might find this hard to digest,</i>

35:37.678 --> 35:41.724
<i>but middle school students</i>
<i>in East Hampton are turning their backs</i>

35:41.807 --> 35:44.685
<i>on staples like pizza and burgers.</i>

35:44.769 --> 35:47.520
I never knew it could
affect my body that bad.

35:47.604 --> 35:49.606
Like, I knew something was going on,

35:49.690 --> 35:53.110
but nothing that bad and gross inside.

35:53.193 --> 35:55.528
[News Anchor]
<i>So a group of kids staged a boycott</i>

35:55.612 --> 35:58.615
<i>and just said no to cafeteria food.</i>

35:58.699 --> 36:00.785
We want fruit. We want vegetables.

36:00.868 --> 36:02.912
We want all the things
you're telling us to eat.

36:02.995 --> 36:06.123
[Cross] <i>The outcome of the boycott</i>
<i>was a lunchroom cooler</i>

36:06.206 --> 36:08.918
<i>that would contain healthy options </i>
<i>for the kids.</i>

36:09.001 --> 36:10.836
An anonymous donor...

36:10.920 --> 36:13.047
Donor, yeah, donated the money
that we needed for the cooler.

36:13.130 --> 36:14.674
[Cross]
<i>That donor was Doug Mercer,</i>

36:14.757 --> 36:18.218
<i>a local resident</i>
<i>who was so inspired by the kids' actions</i>

36:18.301 --> 36:22.098
<i>that he put his hand in his own pocket</i>
<i>and paid for that cooler.</i>

36:22.180 --> 36:25.225
Wonderful article in our local
<i>East Hampton Star</i> paper

36:25.308 --> 36:28.938
and a picture of the kids
boycotting the unhealthy food

36:29.021 --> 36:31.439
at the middle school cafeteria.

36:31.523 --> 36:35.402
<i>And I said, if these kids</i>
<i>can stand up for their health,</i>

36:35.485 --> 36:39.322
<i>I told them that I would buy</i>
<i>the refrigerator case that they needed.</i>

36:41.117 --> 36:42.659
[Ruby]
<i>Once the refrigerator came in,</i>

36:42.743 --> 36:45.871
<i>I remember there were, like,</i>
<i>yogurt parfaits, and nice salads,</i>

36:45.955 --> 36:47.164
<i>and that's what kids were wanting.</i>

36:47.247 --> 36:48.165
<i>And it tasted better.</i>

36:48.248 --> 36:50.458
<i>You felt better after. </i>
<i>You had more energy.</i>

36:55.089 --> 36:58.008
<i>That must have been so empowering for us,</i>

36:58.092 --> 36:59.051
because we were kids,

36:59.135 --> 37:02.387
and how often do you get
taken seriously by adults?

37:02.470 --> 37:04.389
<i>So, for us</i>
<i>to be getting, like, attention--</i>

37:04.472 --> 37:07.143
-To have a voice.
-To have a voice and be listened to...

37:07.225 --> 37:08.643
