to grow a garden at home now.

48:45.381 --> 48:46.215
But it's so cool,

48:46.298 --> 48:48.175
because his older brothers
never had this experience,

48:48.259 --> 48:49.761
and he's learned so much from them.

48:49.845 --> 48:53.013
But now, he can teach them
about things he's learning here,

48:53.097 --> 48:55.391
about foods, and, you know, planting,

48:55.475 --> 48:57.143
and growing, and picking, and making.

48:57.226 --> 49:00.938
Part of the challenge is that
parts of the country struggle with issues

49:01.021 --> 49:03.023
around access
and affordability of healthy food.

49:03.107 --> 49:05.861
It's not the desire,
but there are some barriers

49:05.943 --> 49:08.738
to people being able
to live a healthier life

49:08.822 --> 49:10.156
and being able to make changes.

49:10.239 --> 49:12.701
<i>If it's not easy for families,</i>
<i>they're gonna fail.</i>

49:12.784 --> 49:16.287
So, we have to make it easier for them
to make healthier choices.

49:16.370 --> 49:17.873
I think that's at the crux of the work.

49:19.081 --> 49:22.836
[Cross] <i>One group trying to improve</i>
<i>affordability of fresh produce</i>

49:22.919 --> 49:25.630
<i>for lower-income families</i>
<i>is Wholesome Wave.</i>

49:25.714 --> 49:29.468
<i>Its founder, Michel Nischan,</i>
<i>is a celebrity chef from New York City</i>

49:29.551 --> 49:33.722
<i>who now devotes his life</i>
<i>to helping struggling families eat better.</i>

49:33.805 --> 49:36.600
<i>I wanted to find out</i>
<i>why he left the restaurant world</i>

49:36.683 --> 49:41.103
<i>in order to help improve access</i>
<i>to healthy food for families in need.</i>

49:41.187 --> 49:42.939
This is the smell...

49:44.273 --> 49:45.817
of a perfectly cooked frittata.

49:47.652 --> 49:50.196
[Michel Nischan] <i>I had a restaurant </i>
<i>I owned called Heartbeat,</i>

49:50.279 --> 49:53.700
and it was a restaurant
of local, organic, sustainable cuisine,

49:53.783 --> 49:55.869
but no processed food of any kind.

49:55.952 --> 49:57.453
And I was feeling really good
about myself.

49:58.245 --> 50:02.667
<i>But here I was in a restaurant,</i>
<i>providing healthy food</i>

50:02.751 --> 50:05.879
<i>for people that could afford</i>
<i>to spend $40 on an entree.</i>

50:06.963 --> 50:11.425
<i>At age five, my son Chris was diagnosed</i>
<i>with type 1 diabetes,</i>

50:11.510 --> 50:16.013
<i>and that's where I made the connection</i>
<i>between food and human health.</i>

50:16.096 --> 50:18.224
<i>And then I learned about type 2 diabetes,</i>

50:18.307 --> 50:21.060
<i>that most people that suffer from it</i>
<i>don't have an income</i>

50:21.143 --> 50:24.689
that allows them to buy the food
that can prevent this horrible disease.

50:24.773 --> 50:27.149
So I just... I couldn't reconcile that.

50:28.234 --> 50:29.945
<i>So we founded Wholesome Wave </i>
<i>to figure out </i>

50:30.027 --> 50:33.364
<i>what are some commonsense ways</i>
<i>that we can demonstrate</i>

50:33.447 --> 50:36.660
<i>that people struggling with poverty</i>
<i>really wanna feed their families well.</i>

50:36.743 --> 50:39.829
<i>They would make better food choices</i>
<i>if they could afford it.</i>

50:39.913 --> 50:44.166
So we just said, "Let's create two-for-one
fruit and vegetable sales."

50:44.250 --> 50:47.461
<i>So we started raising private money</i>
<i>to double the value of food stamps.</i>

50:49.505 --> 50:51.090
<i>And it's turned in to such a huge thing.</i>

50:51.173 --> 50:55.887
<i>I got such great reception</i>
<i>from consumers struggling with poverty,</i>

50:55.971 --> 50:58.890
<i>and the farmers, and the markets,</i>
<i>and the local policymakers.</i>

51:00.516 --> 51:02.644
When we started our programs in 2008,

51:02.727 --> 51:05.647
less than 100 farmers' markets
accepted food stamps.

51:05.730 --> 51:09.734
<i>Today, 6,600 of the 8,800</i>
<i>accept food stamps.</i>

51:10.819 --> 51:12.194
So, Michel, you've also created

51:12.278 --> 51:14.781
this Fruit and Vegetable
Prescription Program.

51:14.864 --> 51:16.741
What's that, mate?

51:16.825 --> 51:20.369
[Nischan] <i>So, a patient who is at risk of </i>
<i>a diet-related disease goes to a doctor.</i>

51:20.452 --> 51:23.623
<i>The doctor says, "Yep, you're at risk."</i>
<i>Gives them a prescription.</i>

51:23.707 --> 51:25.959
<i>Tells them to increase </i>
<i>their fruit and vegetable consumption </i>

51:26.042 --> 51:27.043
<i>a serving per day.</i>

51:27.126 --> 51:30.546
<i>And the whole family participates,</i>
<i>so the patient is not in isolation.</i>

51:30.630 --> 51:31.923
<i>So they go the farmers' market,</i>

51:32.007 --> 51:34.550
<i>exchange the prescription</i>
<i>for free fruits and vegetables,</i>

51:34.634 --> 51:36.343
<i>eat more fruits and vegetables,</i>

51:36.427 --> 51:37.929
<i>then go back monthly to be measured</i>

51:38.013 --> 51:39.806
<i>for their health outcomes </i>
<i>and their progress,</i>

51:39.889 --> 51:41.641
<i>and then they get a refill</i>
<i>for their prescription.</i>

51:41.725 --> 51:43.727
So doctors, who are often frustrated

51:43.810 --> 51:46.186
because all they can do
is advise a low-income consumer

51:46.270 --> 51:48.023
that they should be making
healthier food choices,

51:48.105 --> 51:50.399
<i>can actually give that advice.</i>

51:50.482 --> 51:53.695
<i>And then the prescription</i>
<i>actually allows that consumer</i>

51:53.778 --> 51:57.197
<i>to get the free fresh fruits</i>
<i>and vegetables they need.</i>

51:57.281 --> 52:01.160
<i>We use exactly the same infrastructure</i>
<i>of the prescription system,</i>

52:01.243 --> 52:03.955
but we're investing in food
in the front end

52:04.039 --> 52:07.834
instead of paying for medicine for life,
because now, it's too late.

52:08.918 --> 52:11.796
[Cross] <i>One of the doctors who signed up </i>
<i>to work with Wholesome Wave</i>

52:11.880 --> 52:15.507
<i>is Dr. Periasamy at the Harlem Hospital.</i>

52:15.591 --> 52:18.177
